165
00:11:44,970 --> 00:11:46,767
- Connected?
- Yeah.

166
00:11:46,906 --> 00:11:50,467
Like you're thinking about other things.
Is your hair messed up?

167
00:11:50,543 --> 00:11:53,478
Did you buy the toothpaste?
You're just not there.

168
00:11:53,579 --> 00:11:57,640
This kind of disconnect is often
a symptom of a deeper problem.

169
00:11:57,717 --> 00:12:01,847
So we were talking and the idea
of a sexual surrogate came up.

170
00:12:01,954 --> 00:12:05,890
This is a licensed professional
who'd work with you as a couple

171
00:12:05,991 --> 00:12:08,926
on solving whatever sexual problems
you may be having.

172
00:12:08,994 --> 00:12:11,462
I have an excellent referral.

173
00:12:11,530 --> 00:12:15,261
And what would this
sexual surrogate person do?

174
00:12:15,367 --> 00:12:17,767
- She would coach us.
- She?

175
00:12:17,870 --> 00:12:20,771
She's very discreet.
You'll hardly notice she's there.

176
00:12:20,873 --> 00:12:26,402
Oh. So she would be in the room with us
while we make love?

177
00:12:26,512 --> 00:12:30,676
Yes. Helping us to achieve
maximum sexual potential.

178
00:12:32,485 --> 00:12:36,216
- Do you have any questions?
- Just one.

179
00:12:36,288 --> 00:12:39,155
How much longer
is your mid-life crisis going to last?

180
00:12:39,225 --> 00:12:42,786
Because it is really starting
to tick me off.

181
00:12:55,274 --> 00:12:57,640
Right. Everyone's down for a nap.

182
00:12:57,743 --> 00:13:00,906
We've got no more than an hour.
Let's get cracking.

183
00:13:00,980 --> 00:13:03,346
Five-card draw. Nothing wild.

184
00:13:06,452 --> 00:13:09,717
- How is it going with Mike, Susan?
- It's going, finally.

185
00:13:09,789 --> 00:13:13,350
We have a date next week. He's taking me
to see a play or something.

186
00:13:13,425 --> 00:13:17,691
Might I suggest the Barcliff Academy
production of Little Red Riding Hood?

187
00:13:17,763 --> 00:13:20,527
Oh, that's right.
The twins' stage debut.

188
00:13:20,666 --> 00:13:23,294
- Are they having fun?
- Sure. They play oak trees.

189
00:13:23,402 --> 00:13:26,098
I have to deal with the drama
behind the scenes.

190
00:13:26,172 --> 00:13:29,141
- You've met Maisy Gibbons?
- She's a total nightmare.

191
00:13:29,241 --> 00:13:31,869
- I shouldn't have challenged her.
- Oh, dear.

192
00:13:31,977 --> 00:13:34,639
Now no one on the play committee
wants to talk to me.

193
00:13:34,747 --> 00:13:37,875
Maisy does love
to rule her little kingdom.

194
00:13:37,950 --> 00:13:41,408
Hasn't changed since Girl Scouts.
Girls smile at you to your face

195
00:13:41,487 --> 00:13:44,650
then make fun of you
'cause you're not shaving your legs yet.

196
00:13:44,757 --> 00:13:48,090
- [Car horn]
- That wouldn't happen in Boy Scouts.

197
00:13:48,160 --> 00:13:50,993
When I worked with men,
I preferred how they fought.

198
00:13:51,096 --> 00:13:53,587
A guy takes his opponent on
face-to-face,

199
00:13:53,666 --> 00:13:55,725
and once he's won, he's top dog.

200
00:13:57,236 --> 00:14:00,171
- It's primitive but it's fair.
- And a lot less sneaky.

201
00:14:00,272 --> 00:14:03,867
Isn't it sexist of us
to generalize like this?

202
00:14:03,943 --> 00:14:07,344
It's science. Sociologists
have documented this stuff.

203
00:14:07,446 --> 00:14:10,711
Well, who am I
to argue with sociologists?

204
00:14:13,018 --> 00:14:16,954
Wow, this guacamole has got a kick.

205
00:14:17,022 --> 00:14:21,288
I'm gonna run to the little girl's room.
You go ahead. I might be a while.

206
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:24,454
I hate playing three-handed poker.
Let's take a break.

207
00:14:24,530 --> 00:14:27,624
- I'll play.
- You play poker?

208
00:14:27,700 --> 00:14:30,569
- I used to play with my grandfather.
- Pull up a chair.

209
00:14:30,569 --> 00:14:32,696
You're just playing for chips?

210
00:14:32,805 --> 00:14:37,435
My grandfather used to say
it's always more fun to play for money.

211
00:14:37,509 --> 00:14:39,977
- Why not? 50 cents a bet?
- Make it a buck.

212
00:14:40,045 --> 00:14:42,479
Three raise limit, $20 buy-in.

213
00:15:10,476 --> 00:15:15,880
- Mrs. Solis! What are you doing?
- Why haven't you returned my calls?

214
00:15:16,982 --> 00:15:20,008
- I've been busy.
- I've seen who you've been busy with.

215
00:15:20,085 --> 00:15:23,646
Danielle? Come on. She's just a friend.

216
00:15:23,722 --> 00:15:26,452
Before you get any friendlier,
let me remind you,

217
00:15:26,558 --> 00:15:29,083
I can do things to you
she can't even pronounce.

218
00:15:29,161 --> 00:15:33,063
A lot of good it does me with your
mother-in-law following you around.

219
00:15:33,132 --> 00:15:36,033
Maybe we should just cool it
for a while.

220
00:15:36,101 --> 00:15:38,035
No, John, please don't say that.

221
00:15:38,103 --> 00:15:40,799
I have everything under control.

222
00:15:45,611 --> 00:15:48,171
Now give me a boost.

223
00:15:48,247 --> 00:15:50,715
Hey. So what did I miss?

224
00:15:50,783 --> 00:15:54,913
Not much. Just a few friendly hands
of poker with the girls.

225
00:16:10,803 --> 00:16:13,067
I'm sorry I'm late.

226
00:16:13,138 --> 00:16:17,973
As I'm sure you've all heard, Celia Bond
broke her wrist playing tennis.

227
00:16:18,043 --> 00:16:21,740
Which means we are now in need
of someone to do the costumes.

228
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:25,272
I'm keeping my fingers crossed.
Are there any volunteers?

229
00:16:25,351 --> 00:16:29,447
- I'll do it.
- Really? Do you know how to sew?

230
00:16:29,521 --> 00:16:31,955
Absolutely.

231
00:16:32,024 --> 00:16:35,152
Well, great. Thank you, Lynette.

